@node "S_INTRO" "Introduktion"
@toc "S_TOC"
@next "S_USAGE"
@prev "S_TOC"
Efter att ha läst ett antal möten pĺ Usenet sĺ insĺg jag att det behövdes ett UnSplit program till Amigan, sĺ att man slapp fĺ tio splittade brev istället för ett. Detta är resultatet av en mĺnads arbete.
@endnode

@node "E_INTRO" "Introduction"
@toc "E_TOC"
@next "E_USAGE"
@prev "E_TOC"
After having read a few Usenet groups I decided that there was a demand for an UnSplit program for the Amiga, so that you would get only one message instead of ten splitted. This is the result of a months work.
@endnode

@node "E_USAGE" "Usage"
@toc "E_TOC"
@next "E_AUTHOR"
@prev "E_INTRO"
The program works on PKT files, and you can put it in the packing if you're running a tosser or in the import if you're running a pointprogram (e.g. Spot). As I'm pointing of my own node, and run Spot as my pointprogram, I've put it in the _Import.spot script. For some examples, see @{"examples" link "E_EXAMPLES"}.

If you start the program like this:

UnSplit ?

you'll get a template for the program. The template looks like this:

PKTNAME/A,BAD_DIR/A,I=INBUFFER/K/N,O=OUTBUFFER/K/N,R=ROWBUFFER/K/N,REPLACETAG= TAG/K:

PKTNAME:   Here you specify the name of the PKT file that the program should "unsplit". You can use wildcards if you like, e.g. #?.PKT.

BAD_DIR:   This is the working directory for the program. The program copies the PKT files to this directory before it starts to work with them, and then a new file is created in the directory that the PKT file was in at the beginning. If it, against all odds, should be a bad packet or if something goes wrong, then the file will be renamed to *.BAD and recide in BAD_DIR. BAD_DIR can be Mail:Bad or something. Make sure that BAD_DIR is a directory and not a file. I'm thinking of putting in some sort of check for this in a later version, men until then you'll have to make sure it's a directory.

INBUFFER:  Here you specify the size, in KB, that the inbuffer should have. The inbuffer is the buffer that I use when reading the PKT file, a little piece each time. If you don't specify anything, or if you specify less than 8 KB, then the size of the buffer will be 8 KB.

OUTBUFFER: Here you specify the size, in KB, that the outbuffer should have. The outbuffer is the buffer that I use when putting together the new PKT file. If you don't specify anything, or if you specify less than 8 KB, then the size of the buffer will be 8 KB.

ROWBUFFER: Here you specify the size, in KB, that the rowbuffer should have. The rowbuffer is the buffer that I use when fetching a row from the inbuffer. If you don't specify anything, or if you specify less than 8 KB, thenthe size of the buffer will be 8 KB.

REPLACETAG: This is an optional choice, where you can specify a tag file containing which tagnames should be replaced. I added this option when my BBS program could only handle tagnames of max 20 chars, so I had to replace a lot of my Usenet areas with shorter tags. My BBS program now handles longer tags, but I thought it could be good to still have the option. The tags file should look like this:

<tagname> <replace name>

e.g.

COMP.SYS.AMIGA.PROGRAMMER CSA.PROGRAMMER

There is quite much errorchecking in the program, so if, for example, the rowbuffer should be too small when the program fetch a new row, then you'll get an error message telling you the rowbuffer is too small. Then you'll only have to increase the size of the rowbuffer and run the program again. I haven't come across a PKT file that has contained a row longer than 1300 bytes, so 8 KB should be enough for the rowbuffer.
@endnode

